Bring a medium #pot of salted water to a boil. Pat @chicken breasts{12%ounce} dry 
with #paper towels; season all over with @salt{}, @pepper{}, and @herbes de
Provence{1%tsp}. Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{} in a large pan over medium-high
heat. Add chicken and cook until browned and cooked through, ~{5-7%minutes} per
side. Remove chicken from pan and set aside. Wipe out pan.

Meanwhile, wash and dry all produce. Halve, peel, and thinly slice @shallot{1}. 
Halve @grape tomatoes{4%ounce}. Mince or grate @garlic{2%cloves}. Pick @parsley{1/4%ounce} 
leaves from stems; discard stems. Finely chop leaves.

Once water boils, add half the @orzo pasta{6%ounce} to #pot (use all the orzo for
4 servings). Cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}. Drain
thoroughly and return to pot.

Heat a drizzle of olive oil in same pan used to cook chicken over medium heat. Add
shallot; cook until softened, ~{2-3%minutes}. Increase heat to medium-high and add
tomatoes, garlic, @sugar{1/2%tsp}, @herbes de Provence{1/2%tsp}, and half the 
@red wine vinegar{5%tsp}. Cook until thickened and saucy, ~{2%minutes}. Stir in
@chicken demi-glace{1} and @water{2%TBSP}. Bring to a simmer, then turn off heat.
Stir in @butter{1%TBSP}. Season with salt and pepper.

Stir @pesto{2%ounce}, @butter{1%TBSP}, and @parmesan cheese{1/4%cup} into #pot with
drained orzo. Season with salt and pepper.

Divide chicken and orzo between plates. Top chicken with pan sauce, making sure to
include tomatoes. Garnish with parsley and remaining parmesan cheese.

> This meal packs sophistication for adults while keeping things kid-friendly. 
> The burst tomatoes simmered in sauce make them extra flavorful and juicy.
> For picky eaters, serve the sauce on the side.